WEBVTT

00:15.667 --> 00:18.333
<i>My name is Mary Alice Young.</i>

00:18.417 --> 00:21.417
<i>In this morning's paper,</i>
<i>you may come across an article</i>

00:21.542 --> 00:24.834
<i>about the unusual day I had last week.</i>

00:24.917 --> 00:28.458
<i>Normally, there's never anything</i>
<i>newsworthy about my life,</i>

00:28.542 --> 00:31.333
<i>but that all changed last Thursday.</i>

00:31.417 --> 00:35.166
<i>Of course, everything seemed</i>
<i>quite normal at first.</i>

00:35.250 --> 00:37.083
<i>I made breakfast for my family.</i>

00:39.083 --> 00:41.291
<i>I performed my chores.</i>

00:42.750 --> 00:45.458
<i>I completed my projects.</i>

00:46.500 --> 00:49.083
<i>I ran my errands.</i>

00:49.166 --> 00:53.375
<i>In truth, I spent the day</i>
<i>as I spent every other day,</i>

00:53.458 --> 00:59.834
<i>quietly polishing the routine of my life</i>
<i>until it gleamed with perfection.</i>

01:02.125 --> 01:06.875
<i>That's why it was so astonishing when</i>
<i>I decided to go to my hallway closet</i>

01:06.959 --> 01:11.709
<i>and retrieve a revolver</i>
<i>that had never been used.</i>

01:16.083 --> 01:20.583
<i>My body was discovered</i>
<i>by my neighbor, Mrs. Martha Huber,</i>

01:20.667 --> 01:24.125
<i>who'd been startled</i>
<i>by a strange popping sound.</i>

01:24.208 --> 01:26.291
<i>Her curiosity aroused,</i>

01:26.375 --> 01:30.166
<i>Mrs. Huber tried to think of a reason</i>
<i>for dropping in on me unannounced.</i>

01:33.083 --> 01:35.333
<i>After some initial hesitation,</i>

01:35.417 --> 01:40.834
<i>she decided to return the blender she</i>
<i>had borrowed from me six months before.</i>

02:02.625 --> 02:06.625
It's my neighbor. I think she's been
shot. There's blood everywhere.

02:06.709 --> 02:09.625
Yes, you've got to send an ambulance.

02:09.709 --> 02:12.583
You've got to send one right now.

02:16.333 --> 02:20.625
<i>And, for a moment, Mrs. Huber</i>
<i>stood motionless in her kitchen,</i>

02:20.709 --> 02:23.709
<i>grief-stricken</i>
<i>by this senseless tragedy.</i>

02:23.834 --> 02:26.417
<i>But only for a moment.</i>

02:26.542 --> 02:29.291
<i>If there was one thing</i>
<i>Mrs. Huber was known for,</i>

02:30.083 --> 02:33.208
<i>it was her ability</i>
<i>to look on the bright side.</i>

02:39.834 --> 02:42.291
<i>I was laid to rest on a Monday.</i>

02:42.375 --> 02:45.500
<i>After the funeral,</i>
<i>all the residents of Wisteria Lane</i>

02:45.583 --> 02:48.458
<i>came to pay their respects.</i>

02:48.583 --> 02:52.750
<i>And, as people do in these situations,</i>
<i>they brought food.</i>

02:52.834 --> 02:55.417
<i>Lynette Scavo brought fried chicken.</i>

02:55.500 --> 02:58.583
<i>Lynette had a great family recipe</i>
<i>for fried chicken.</i>

02:58.667 --> 03:02.291
<i>She didn't cook much</i>
<i>while moving up the corporate ladder.</i>

03:02.417 --> 03:04.125
<i>She didn't have the time.</i>

03:04.208 --> 03:08.750
<i>But when her doctor announced she was</i>
<i>pregnant, her husband Tom had an idea.</i>

03:08.834 --> 03:10.583
<i>"Why not quit your job?"</i>

03:10.667 --> 03:15.125
<i>"Kids do better with stay-at-home moms.</i>
<i>It would be so much less stressful."</i>

03:15.250 --> 03:17.208
<i>But this was not the case.</i>

03:17.291 --> 03:20.375
<i>In fact, Lynette's life</i>
<i>had become so hectic</i>

03:20.458 --> 03:24.583
<i>she was now forced to get her chicken</i>
<i>from the fast-food restaurant.</i>

03:24.667 --> 03:28.375
<i>Lynette would've appreciated the irony</i>
<i>if she'd thought about it.</i>

03:28.458 --> 03:30.542
<i>But she didn't have the time.</i>

03:30.625 --> 03:32.875
- Stop it, stop it, stop it.
- But, Mom.

03:32.959 --> 03:35.125
No. You are going to behave today.

03:35.208 --> 03:38.542
I am not going to be humiliated
in front of the entire neighborhood.

03:38.834 --> 03:41.542
And, just so you know
how serious I am...

03:41.625 --> 03:44.834
- What's that?
- Santa's cell-phone number.

03:44.917 --> 03:46.709
How did you get that?

03:46.792 --> 03:49.625
I know someone
who knows someone who knows an elf.

03:49.709 --> 03:52.625
And if any of you acts up,
so help me, I will call Santa

03:52.750 --> 03:56.667
and I will tell him
you want socks for Christmas.

03:56.792 --> 03:58.875
Are you willing to risk that?

04:00.375 --> 04:04.625
OK. Let's get this over with.

04:07.834 --> 04:12.750
<i>Gabrielle Solis who lives down the block</i>
<i>brought a spicy paella.</i>

04:13.417 --> 04:17.250
<i>Since her modeling days in New York,</i>
<i>Gabrielle had developed a taste</i>

04:17.333 --> 04:19.709
<i>for rich food</i>

04:19.834 --> 04:22.000
<i>and rich men.</i>

04:22.792 --> 04:25.500
<i>Carlos, who worked in mergers</i>
<i>and acquisitions,</i>

04:25.583 --> 04:27.417
<i>proposed on their third date.</i>

04:27.500 --> 04:30.834
<i>Gabrielle was touched</i>
<i>when tears welled up in his eyes.</i>

04:30.917 --> 04:35.583
<i>But she soon discovered this happened</i>
<i>every time Carlos closed a big deal.</i>

04:35.667 --> 04:38.500
<i>Gabrielle liked her paella piping hot.</i>

04:38.583 --> 04:43.000
<i>However, her relationship with</i>
<i>her husband was considerably cooler.</i>

04:43.125 --> 04:45.417
If you talk to Al Mason at this thing,

04:45.500 --> 04:47.917
mention how much
I paid for your necklace.

04:48.000 --> 04:50.125
Why not pin the receipt to my chest?

04:50.208 --> 04:53.208
He let me know what he paid
for his wife's convertible.

04:53.291 --> 04:55.417
- Just work it in.
- There's no way I can.

04:55.542 --> 04:59.709
Why not? At the Donahue party
everyone was talking mutual funds.

04:59.792 --> 05:03.041
You mentioned
you slept with half the Yankee outfield.

05:03.125 --> 05:05.792
It came up
in the context of the conversation.

05:05.875 --> 05:08.208
People are staring.
Keep your voice down.

05:08.333 --> 05:11.625
Absolutely. We wouldn't want them
to think we're not happy.

05:11.709 --> 05:14.250
<i>Bree Van De Kamp, who lives next door,</i>

05:14.375 --> 05:17.208
<i>brought baskets of muffins</i>
<i>she baked from scratch.</i>

05:17.333 --> 05:22.208
<i>Bree was known for her cooking.</i>
<i>And for making her own clothes.</i>

05:22.959 --> 05:25.125
<i>And for doing her own gardening.</i>

05:25.709 --> 05:29.166
<i>And for re-upholstering</i>
<i>her own furniture.</i>

05:29.250 --> 05:33.000
<i>Yes, Bree's many talents were known</i>
<i>throughout the neighborhood.</i>

05:33.083 --> 05:37.750
<i>Everyone on Wisteria Lane thought</i>
<i>of Bree as the perfect wife and mother.</i>

05:37.875 --> 05:41.709
<i>Everyone, that is,</i>
<i>except her own family.</i>

05:44.458 --> 05:46.750
Paul. Zachary.

05:46.875 --> 05:49.959
- Hello, Mrs. Van De Kamp.
- You shouldn't have.

05:50.083 --> 05:54.250
It was no trouble. The basket
with the red ribbon is for your guests.

05:54.375 --> 05:57.333
The one with the blue ribbon
is for you and Zachary.

05:57.417 --> 06:00.333
It's got rolls, muffins,
breakfast type things.

06:00.417 --> 06:01.667
Thank you.

06:01.750 --> 06:04.542
The least I could do
was give you a decent meal

06:04.625 --> 06:06.458
to look forward to in the morning.

06:06.583 --> 06:09.250
I know you're
out of your minds with grief.

06:09.375 --> 06:11.583
Yes, we are.

06:13.000 --> 06:15.625
I will need
the baskets back once you're done.

06:16.959 --> 06:18.375
Of course.

06:22.250 --> 06:24.583
<i>Susan Mayer,</i>
<i>who lives across the street,</i>

06:24.667 --> 06:26.834
<i>brought macaroni and cheese.</i>

06:26.959 --> 06:30.125
<i>Her husband, Karl,</i>
<i>always teased her about her macaroni,</i>

06:30.208 --> 06:34.625
<i>saying it was the only thing she knew</i>
<i>how to cook and she rarely made it well.</i>

06:35.166 --> 06:38.625
<i>It was too salty the night</i>
<i>she and Karl moved into their house.</i>

06:39.458 --> 06:42.959
<i>It was too watery the night</i>
<i>she found lipstick on Karl's shirt.</i>

06:44.083 --> 06:48.458
<i>She burned it the night Karl told her</i>
<i>he was leaving her for his secretary.</i>

06:56.291 --> 06:58.750
<i>A year had passed since the divorce.</i>

06:58.834 --> 07:02.458
<i>Susan had started to think it would</i>
<i>be nice to have a man in her life.</i>

07:02.542 --> 07:04.959
<i>Even one who would</i>
<i>make fun of her cooking.</i>

07:05.041 --> 07:08.208
Mom, why would
someone kill themselves?

07:09.625 --> 07:12.834
Well, sometimes people are so unhappy,

07:12.959 --> 07:16.000
they think that's the only way
to solve their problems.

07:16.083 --> 07:18.750
- Mrs. Young always seemed happy.
- Yeah.

07:18.834 --> 07:23.375
