19:04.417 --> 19:10.166
You know, Mrs. Solis,
I really like it when we hook up,

19:10.250 --> 19:13.458
but, you know,
I got to get my work done

19:13.542 --> 19:15.875
and I can't afford to lose this job.

19:18.208 --> 19:23.041
This table was hand-carved.
Carlos had it imported from Italy.

19:23.125 --> 19:26.917
It cost him $23,000.

19:27.000 --> 19:30.083
You want to do it
on the table this time?

19:30.208 --> 19:32.750
Absolutely.

19:47.875 --> 19:49.917
Why can't we ever have normal soup?

19:50.000 --> 19:53.458
Danielle, there is nothing abnormal
about basil purée.

19:53.583 --> 19:56.083
Once, can we have a soup
people have heard of?

19:56.208 --> 20:00.500
- Like French onion or navy bean?
- Your father can't eat onions.

20:00.583 --> 20:05.834
He's deathly allergic. And I won't even
dignify your navy bean suggestion.

20:05.917 --> 20:08.959
So, how's the osso bucco?

20:09.083 --> 20:12.166
- It's OK.
- It's OK?

20:12.875 --> 20:15.458
I spent three hours cooking this meal.

20:15.583 --> 20:19.583
How do you think it feels when you say,
"It's OK" in that sullen tone?

20:19.709 --> 20:23.041
Who asked you to spend three hours
on dinner?

20:25.375 --> 20:27.959
Excuse me?

20:28.041 --> 20:31.709
Tim Harper's mom gets home from work,
opens a can of pork and beans,

20:31.834 --> 20:33.875
they're eating, everyone's happy.

20:33.959 --> 20:37.375
- You'd rather I served pork and beans?
- Apologize now, I beg.

20:37.458 --> 20:41.291
Do you always have to serve cuisine?
Can't we just have food?

20:41.375 --> 20:43.375
- Are you doing drugs?
- What?

20:43.458 --> 20:45.500
Change in behavior
is a warning sign

20:45.583 --> 20:48.792
and you have been as fresh as paint
for the last six months.

20:48.875 --> 20:51.458
It explains why you're always
in the bathroom.

20:51.542 --> 20:53.834
- That is not what he's doing.
- Shut up.

20:53.959 --> 20:56.625
Mom, I'm not the one
with the problem here.

20:56.709 --> 20:59.792
You're the one acting like
she's running for Mayor of Stepford.

21:00.834 --> 21:04.000
Rex, seeing that
you're the head of this household,

21:04.083 --> 21:06.333
I'd appreciate you saying something.

21:08.875 --> 21:11.000
Pass the salt?

21:22.834 --> 21:24.417
<i>Three days after my funeral,</i>

21:24.500 --> 21:28.500
<i>Lynette replaced her grief</i>
<i>with a much more useful emotion.</i>

21:28.583 --> 21:29.667
<i>Indignation.</i>

21:29.792 --> 21:33.583
Tom, this is my fifth message
and you still haven't called me back.

21:33.667 --> 21:38.625
You must be having a lot of fun on
your business trip. I can only imagine.

21:38.709 --> 21:41.417
Guess what,
the kids and I want some fun too,

21:41.542 --> 21:45.291
so unless you call me back by noon,
we're getting a plane to join you.

21:45.375 --> 21:48.458
- Mom.
- Not now. Mommy's threatening Daddy.

21:48.542 --> 21:51.166
- Mom.
- No, I...

21:51.250 --> 21:54.542
- Where are your brothers?
- Noodles, my favorite.

22:01.166 --> 22:03.709
- Lynette Scavo?
- Crap.

22:03.792 --> 22:07.375
Natalie Klein. I don't believe it.

22:07.458 --> 22:13.542
- Lynette. How long has it been?
- Years. How are you? How's the firm?

22:13.625 --> 22:16.875
- Good. Everyone misses you.
- Yeah.

22:17.000 --> 22:20.333
We all say, if you hadn't quit
you'd be running the place now.

22:20.417 --> 22:22.834
Yeah, well.

22:22.917 --> 22:27.625
So how's domestic life?

22:27.709 --> 22:30.000
Don't you just love being a mom?

22:30.083 --> 22:34.417
<i>And there it was. The question</i>
<i>that Lynette always dreaded.</i>

22:34.542 --> 22:36.208
Well, to be honest...

22:36.291 --> 22:40.000
<i>For those who asked it,</i>
<i>only one answer was acceptable.</i>

22:40.083 --> 22:43.917
<i>So Lynette responded</i>
<i>as she always did. She lied.</i>

22:44.000 --> 22:46.834
It's the best job I've ever had.

22:58.375 --> 23:00.667
- You know what I don't get?
- What?

23:00.792 --> 23:02.667
Why you married Mr. Solis.

23:06.125 --> 23:11.917
Well, he promised to give me
everything I've ever wanted.

23:12.000 --> 23:16.166
- And did he?
- Yes.

23:16.291 --> 23:18.709
Then why aren't you happy?

23:20.417 --> 23:23.834
Turns out I wanted all the wrong things.

23:23.917 --> 23:28.333
So do you love him?

23:28.458 --> 23:29.875
I do.

23:29.959 --> 23:33.291
So then why are we here?
Why are we doing this?

23:33.375 --> 23:35.792
Because I don't want
to wake up one morning

23:35.875 --> 23:38.667
with a sudden urge
to blow my brains out.

23:43.000 --> 23:45.959
- Hey, can I have a drag?
- Absolutely not.

23:46.041 --> 23:49.667
You are much too young to smoke.

23:50.542 --> 23:55.041
How would you feel if I used your child
support payments for plastic surgery?

23:55.166 --> 23:58.583
Stop being nervous. You're asking him
to dinner. No big deal.

23:58.667 --> 24:01.333
You're right.

24:01.458 --> 24:03.250
Is that your project for school?

24:03.333 --> 24:06.583
In fifth grade I made
the White House out of sugar cubes.

24:06.667 --> 24:10.291
Stop stalling and go. Before
Mike figures out he can do better.

24:11.375 --> 24:15.166
Tell me again
why I fought for custody of you.

24:15.291 --> 24:19.458
- You were using me to hurt Dad.
- That's right.

24:21.208 --> 24:22.709
Oh, God.

24:34.041 --> 24:36.375
- Are you busy?
- No, not at all. What's up?

24:36.458 --> 24:41.709
Well, I just was wondering if

24:41.792 --> 24:44.542
there was any chance that you...

24:47.041 --> 24:49.458
I just wanted to ask if...

24:51.125 --> 24:53.125
- Edie.
- Hey, there, Susan.

24:53.208 --> 24:55.792
- What are you...?
- I was making ambrosia.

24:55.875 --> 24:59.667
and I made too much so I thought
I'd bring some over to Mike.

24:59.750 --> 25:02.625
- What's going on?
- Susan was asking me something.

25:09.583 --> 25:11.834
- I have a clog.
- Excuse me?

25:11.917 --> 25:14.959
- And you're a plumber, right?
- Yeah.

25:15.083 --> 25:18.667
- The clog's in the pipe.
- Yeah, that's usually where they are.

25:18.750 --> 25:22.417
- Well, I've got one.
- OK. Let me get my tools.

25:22.500 --> 25:26.166
Now? You want to come over now?
You have company.

25:26.250 --> 25:27.667
I don't mind.

25:27.750 --> 25:31.208
Just give me two minutes.
I'll be right over.

25:40.500 --> 25:41.709
That's it.

25:41.792 --> 25:43.834
- Stuff the hair down.
- I stuffed it.

25:43.959 --> 25:47.542
- It's not enough to clog it.
- Here. Look.

25:47.625 --> 25:49.667
Put in this peanut butter.

25:50.792 --> 25:53.417
And this cooking oil.

25:53.500 --> 25:55.125
- Mom...
- And these olives.

25:55.375 --> 25:57.458
It's not working.

25:58.333 --> 26:01.041
Oh, God. That's him.

26:01.125 --> 26:03.917
How am I gonna stop up the sink?

26:11.208 --> 26:13.834
Well, here's your problem.

26:13.917 --> 26:17.208
Somebody stuffed
a bunch of Popsicle sticks down here.

26:18.125 --> 26:22.667
I've told Julie a million times not to
play in the kitchen. Kids, you know.

26:28.333 --> 26:32.583
I'll go put in your orders and I'll be
back with your plates for the salad bar.

26:32.667 --> 26:34.792
Thank you.

26:34.875 --> 26:37.375
Andrew, Danielle, napkins. Thank you.

26:38.834 --> 26:43.291
They have video games. Can we go play
until our food gets here?

26:43.417 --> 26:47.667
- This is family time. I think...
- Go ahead and play.

26:56.834 --> 26:59.875
I know you think I'm angry
about coming here, but I'm not.

27:00.000 --> 27:03.083
The kids wanted a change of pace,
something fun.

27:03.166 --> 27:07.875
I get it. They'll want something
healthier tomorrow, though.

27:07.959 --> 27:11.208
- I'm thinking chicken saltimbocca.
- I want a divorce.

27:15.208 --> 27:20.583
I just can't live in this
detergent commercial anymore.

27:22.625 --> 27:24.750
The salad bar's there.
Help yourself.

27:24.834 --> 27:27.083
Thank you.

27:29.333 --> 27:32.542
Um, I think I'll go get
your salad for you.

27:44.875 --> 27:49.083
- Bree Van De Kamp.
- Oh, hello, Mrs. Huber.

27:49.750 --> 27:54.083
We didn't get a chance to talk
at Mary Alice's wake. How are you doing?

27:55.250 --> 27:59.417
<i>Bree longed to share the truth</i>
<i>about her husband's painful betrayal.</i>

27:59.542 --> 28:03.750
<i>But sadly for Bree,</i>
<i>admitting defeat was not an option.</i>

28:03.834 --> 28:07.667
Great. Everything is just great.

28:07.750 --> 28:12.750
I got you the honey mustard dressing.
The ranch looked a little bit suspect.

28:22.500 --> 28:24.583
Are we gonna talk about what I said?

28:24.709 --> 28:27.500
If you think I'll discuss
my marriage in a place

28:27.583 --> 28:31.625
with rest-rooms labeled "Chicks"
and "Dudes", you're out of your mind.

28:35.041 --> 28:37.917
- What's in this?
- What do you mean? It's salad.

28:38.000 --> 28:41.166
- With onions.
- What?

28:41.291 --> 28:44.291
- You put onions in my salad.
- No, I didn't.

28:48.917 --> 28:50.333
Oh, wait.

28:58.750 --> 29:02.875
<i>The sound that awakened my son was</i>
<i>something he'd heard only once before.</i>

29:02.959 --> 29:06.500
<i>Many years ago</i>
<i>when he was quite young.</i>

29:09.041 --> 29:11.333
<i>But he recognized it instantly.</i>

29:18.542 --> 29:21.667
<i>It was the sound of a family secret.</i>

29:41.500 --> 29:45.041
<i>Seven days after my funeral,</i>
<i>life on Wisteria Lane</i>

29:45.125 --> 29:47.166
<i>finally returned to normal.</i>

29:48.333 --> 29:52.709
<i>Which, for some of my friends,</i>
<i>was unfortunate.</i>

29:54.458 --> 29:57.458
- Mommy.
- Now what?

29:57.542 --> 29:59.583
Daddy's home.

30:00.625 --> 30:03.875
Come on. Is anybody home?

30:07.458 --> 30:09.625
I wasn't expecting you for a week.

30:09.709 --> 30:12.166
I have to go back to 'Frisco
in the morning.

30:12.250 --> 30:14.500
I got your call. You sounded frazzled.

30:15.875 --> 30:19.083
- It's been a little rough.
- Hi. Yeah. Peaches.

30:19.166 --> 30:20.959
Did you buy us any presents?

30:21.041 --> 30:23.875
Oh, God, presents.
Wait up. Let me see.

30:30.291 --> 30:34.417
But I'm not giving it to you unless you
promise to go outside right now

30:34.500 --> 30:37.083
and practice throwing for 20 minutes.

30:37.166 --> 30:39.667
- Yeah.
- Punks. Get out.

30:39.750 --> 30:44.667
Who's open? Go out.
Deeper. Touchdown.

30:46.208 --> 30:47.583
Oh, my God.

30:52.083 --> 30:57.458
You got to be kidding. I'm exhausted.
I look terrible. I'm covered in peaches.

30:57.583 --> 31:02.792
- I'm sorry, baby. I got to have you.
- Well, is it OK if I just lie here?

31:02.917 --> 31:05.917
Absolutely.

31:08.166 --> 31:13.250
- I love you.
- I love you more... Oh, baby.

31:13.375 --> 31:15.625
I was having trouble with swelling.

31:15.709 --> 31:18.500
The doctor took me off the pill.
Put on a condom.

31:18.583 --> 31:20.041
- A condom?
- Yeah.

31:20.125 --> 31:22.834
What's the big deal? Let's risk it.

31:22.917 --> 31:25.959
- Let's risk it?
- Yeah.

31:35.125 --> 31:39.375
- I can't believe you tried to kill me.
- Yes, well, I feel badly about that.

31:39.458 --> 31:44.041
Mrs. Huber came over and I got
distracted. It was a mistake.

31:44.125 --> 31:47.125
- Since when do you make mistakes?
- What does that mean?

31:47.208 --> 31:52.417
It means I'm sick of you
being so damn perfect all the time.

31:52.500 --> 31:55.834
I'm sick of the bizarre way
your hair doesn't move.

31:55.917 --> 32:00.000
I'm sick of you making our bed in the
morning before I've used the bathroom.

32:00.083 --> 32:04.417
You're this plastic suburban housewife,
with her pearls and spatula,

32:04.500 --> 32:07.834
who says things like
"We owe the Hendersons a dinner."

32:10.291 --> 32:12.458
Where's the woman I fell in love with,

32:14.083 --> 32:18.834
who used to burn the toast
and drink milk out of the carton?

32:20.959 --> 32:23.000
And laugh.

32:25.208 --> 32:31.458
I need her. Not this cold,
perfect thing you've become.

32:38.875 --> 32:41.000
These need water.

32:53.750 --> 32:57.542
<i>Bree sobbed quietly</i>
<i>in the restroom for five minutes,</i>

32:57.667 --> 32:59.709
<i>but her husband never knew.</i>

33:01.041 --> 33:04.250
<i>Because when Bree finally emerged...</i>

33:07.041 --> 33:09.458
<i>...she was perfect.</i>

33:15.834 --> 33:20.000
- I found my earrings. We can go now.
- Was John here today?

33:20.083 --> 33:21.417
Well, yeah.

33:21.542 --> 33:26.291
The lawn hasn't been mowed. I've
had it. We're getting a real gardener.

33:26.375 --> 33:27.709
- Why?
- Are you deaf?

33:27.792 --> 33:30.458
I just said he's not doing his job.

33:30.542 --> 33:33.333
It's dark. You can't see
the lawn has been mowed.

33:33.417 --> 33:36.500
- It hasn't. Feel this grass.
- I'm not feeling the grass.

33:36.583 --> 33:39.917
Let's just get going.
Come on, we're late.

33:46.291 --> 33:48.041
- Take care of it.
- Yes, sir.

33:53.792 --> 33:58.208
There's Tanaka.
Time for me to go and do my dance.

33:58.291 --> 34:00.458
Good luck, sweetheart.

34:03.792 --> 34:06.000
You see that man just walked away?

34:06.125 --> 34:11.959
Can you make sure he has a drink
in his hand all night long?

34:12.834 --> 34:14.125
Yes, ma'am.

35:49.709 --> 35:53.667
- Susan.
- Mrs. Huber, how are you doing?

35:53.750 --> 35:57.917
Not too well, I'm afraid. I'm trying to
find something to soothe my stomach.

35:58.000 --> 36:00.333
- It's upset?
- Yeah.

36:00.417 --> 36:04.709
I had the worst macaroni and cheese at
the wake. It's been running through me.

36:04.834 --> 36:08.917
And I need to be at my best. Edie
Britt's son is spending the night.

36:09.750 --> 36:11.417
He's spending the night?

36:11.500 --> 36:14.625
Edie is having a gentleman friend
over for dinner,

36:14.750 --> 36:18.000
and I think she plans on
entertaining into the wee hours,

36:18.083 --> 36:20.166
if you know what I mean.

36:21.333 --> 36:24.834
Oh, here's some antacid.
Have you ever tried this?

36:25.792 --> 36:28.750
I can't believe it.
This can't be happening.

36:28.834 --> 36:31.125
Mike can't like Edie
better than me.

36:31.208 --> 36:35.625
You don't know what's going on.
Maybe they're just having dinner.

36:35.750 --> 36:38.333
You're right. They're doing it.

36:52.125 --> 36:53.959
Edie?

37:05.125 --> 37:06.625
Edie?

37:12.166 --> 37:15.750
Hello? Anybody home?

37:18.458 --> 37:20.458
I need to borrow sugar.

37:37.375 --> 37:42.041
Oh, my God.
Oh, yes. Give it to me.

37:42.125 --> 37:46.000
<i>And just like that,</i>
<i>the possibility Susan had clung to,</i>

37:46.083 --> 37:51.625
<i>the maybe of Mike Delfino,</i>
<i>was gone forever.</i>

37:53.166 --> 37:55.834
<i>Despite the precariousness</i>
<i>of her situation,</i>

37:55.917 --> 37:58.000
<i>Susan took a moment to mourn her loss.</i>

38:25.625 --> 38:30.208
<i>It didn't take Susan long to realize,</i>
<i>this was just not her night.</i>

38:31.959 --> 38:34.041
Is somebody out there?

38:34.917 --> 38:37.375
Oh, my God. That's smoke.

38:51.917 --> 38:54.250
Oh, my God.

38:55.083 --> 38:57.375
She left candles unattended in the den.

38:57.458 --> 39:00.834
Paramedic said she was lucky.
She could've been killed.

39:00.917 --> 39:03.375
She ran out with nothing on.

39:03.750 --> 39:07.959
- She was having sex with some guy.
- What happened to him?

39:08.083 --> 39:10.750
He got smoke inhalation.
He's at the hospital.

39:12.500 --> 39:15.041
Susan, are you all right?
You look awful.

39:15.125 --> 39:17.375
I'm fine.

39:17.458 --> 39:21.709
I just feel really bad for Edie.

39:21.792 --> 39:24.750
Honey, don't worry about Edie.
She's a strong lady.

39:24.834 --> 39:29.041
Absolutely. She'll get through this.
She'll find a way to survive.

39:29.166 --> 39:31.417
We all do.

39:34.583 --> 39:36.834
Come on.

39:53.750 --> 39:56.375
- What happened?
- Mike.

39:56.458 --> 40:00.834
<i>And suddenly there he was.</i>
<i>Like a phoenix rising from the ashes.</i>

40:00.917 --> 40:05.208
I thought you were...
Where were you?

40:05.291 --> 40:08.834
I just got back from the movies.
Edie had a fire?

40:08.917 --> 40:15.834
Yeah. But she's fine now.
Everything's fine now.

40:15.917 --> 40:18.875
<i>And just like that, Susan was happy.</i>

40:19.000 --> 40:23.667
<i>Life was suddenly full of</i>
<i>possibilities.</i>

40:28.792 --> 40:32.709
<i>Not to mention</i>
<i>a few unexpected surprises.</i>

40:37.542 --> 40:39.083
<i>- Hello?</i>
- It's me.

40:39.166 --> 40:41.291
<i>- Have anything yet?</i>
- No, nothing yet.

40:41.375 --> 40:45.458
But don't worry.
I'm definitely getting closer.

40:53.709 --> 40:57.625
I brought some champagne.
I thought we should have a toast.

40:57.709 --> 41:01.500
<i>The next day my friends came together</i>
<i>to pack away my clothes,</i>

41:01.583 --> 41:06.125
<i>my personal belongings</i>
<i>and what was left of my life.</i>

41:07.709 --> 41:09.792
All right, ladies, lift 'em up.

41:09.875 --> 41:12.959
To Mary Alice,
a good friend and neighbor.

41:13.041 --> 41:15.583
Wherever you are,
we hope you've found peace.

41:15.667 --> 41:18.250
To Mary Alice.

41:24.959 --> 41:26.875
Let's get this show on the road.

41:26.959 --> 41:29.458
You guys,
check out Mary Alice's clothes.

41:29.542 --> 41:33.417
Size eight? Ha.
She always told me she was a size six.

41:33.542 --> 41:38.041
- We found the skeleton in her closet.
<i>- Not quite, Gabrielle, not quite.</i>

41:38.166 --> 41:40.959
- What's that?
- A letter addressed to Mary Alice.

41:41.750 --> 41:43.083
<i>How ironic.</i>

41:43.166 --> 41:47.500
<i>To have something I tried so desperately</i>
<i>to keep secret, treated so casually.</i>

41:47.583 --> 41:51.250
- That's private.
- It's open. What's the big deal?

42:03.375 --> 42:06.500
- What does it mean?
- Don't know. Check out the postmark.

42:06.583 --> 42:09.333
Oh, my God. She got it the day she died.

42:10.917 --> 42:12.625
Do you think this is why she...?

42:13.458 --> 42:18.250
<i>I'm so sorry, girls. I never wanted you</i>
<i>to be burdened with this.</i>

42:20.959 --> 42:23.792
Mary Alice, what did you do?
